<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Saturday, July 14, the 195th day of 1990. There are 170
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 14, 1789, the French Revolution was in full swing as
citizens of Paris stormed the Bastille prison and released the
seven prisoners inside.
   On this date:
   In 1798, Congress passed the Sedition Act, making it a federal
crime to publish false, scandalous or malicious writing about the
United States government.
   In 1853, Commodore Matthew Perry relayed to Japanese officials a
letter from former President Fillmore, requesting trade relations.
   In 1881, outlaw William H. Bonney Jr., alias Billy the Kid, was
shot and killed by Sheriff Pat Garrett in Fort Sumner, N.M.
   In 1921, Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were convicted in
Dedham, Mass., in the killing of a shoe company paymaster and his
guard. Sacco and Vanzetti were executed six years later.
   In 1958, the army of Iraq overthrew the monarchy.
   In 1966, eight student nurses were murdered by Richard Speck in
a Chicago dormitory.
   In 1976, Jimmy Carter won the Democratic presidential nomination
by an overwhelming margin at the party's convention in New York.
   In 1978, Soviet dissident Anatoly Shcharansky was convicted of
treasonous espionage and anti-Soviet agitation, and sentenced to 13
years at hard labor. Shcharansky was released in 1986.
   In 1983, two members of Congress, Illinois Republican Daniel
Crane and Massachusetts Democrat Gerry Studds, admitted having
sexual relations with congressional pages, and were later censured
by the full House.
   Ten years ago: The Republican national convention opened in
Detroit, where nominee-apparent Ronald Reagan told a welcoming
rally he and his supporters were determined to ``make America great
again.''
   Five years ago: Doctors at Bethesda Naval Hospital said
President Reagan was making a spectacular recovery from major
abdominal surgery to remove an intestinal growth that proved to be
cancerous.
   One year ago: Leaders of the seven richest nations opened a
summit in Paris, which was also celebrating the bicentennial of the
French Revolution with pomp and pageantry.
   Today's birthdays: Author Isaac Bashevis Singer is 86. Former
President Ford is 77. Former CBS newscaster Douglas Edwards is 73.
Movie director Ingmar Bergman is 72. NBC News commentator John
Chancellor is 63. Football player-turned-actor Rosey Grier is 58.
   Thought for today: ``It takes people a long time to learn the
difference between talent and genius, especially ambitious young
men and women.'' _ Louisa May Alcott, American author (1832-1888).
</TEXT>
